 A majority of the members of the House of Representatives has signaled support. "It is wrong to apportion congressional seats by counting people who would be deported if our immigration laws were enforced," Rep.
 Wisconsin has few illegal immigrants; Arizona has lots. "It boils down to regional politics," says Arturo Vargas, census-program director for the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, one of several Hispanic organizations lobbying in favor of counting illegal immigrants.
 Ridge dismisses the practical problems. "We're spending billions on the census, and the only thing we get is a bunch of belly-aching about how difficult it will be," he complains. "The primary purpose of the census is to distribute political power . . . not to gather demographic information." The Senate, by a vote of 58-41, added a provision to a pending immigration bill to require the government to subtract illegal immigrants when it comes up with figures used for reapportionment.
